ce:section.ce:para:
In this paper, we prepare a two-dimensional Cu-based ternary chalcogenide nanodot with renal clearable and spatially controlled catalytic features for the management of wound infection (Fig. 1
                     ). Copper (Cu) element is the catalytic factor of many enzymes in the physiological processes and is a required trace element in the human body [21–23]. Therefore, it is reasonable to infer that Cu-based nanomaterials can be used to generate ROS for wound disinfection [24–26]. Recently, Cu-based nanomaterials with enzyme-like activity have received special attentions in antibacterial treatments [27–29]. For example, copper/carbon hybrid nanozyme with peroxidase-like activity can catalyze the generation ROS for antibacterial treatment [24]. The CuCo2S4 nanozyme exhibits intrinsic peroxidase-like activity and can convert H2O2 into 

                     OH for killing bacteria [30]. Nevertheless, these nanozymes show the enzyme-like catalytic activity over broad pH range and fail to spatially generate ROS for overcoming the heterogeneity of wounds and normal tissues. Therefore, the exploring nanozymes with controlled catalytic activity, ROS generation in a specific condition, and biosafety without potential toxicity for normal cells, is still highly desired.
